---

Last week, Donald Trump signed an executive order to accelerate psychedelic research in the United States. You can read our full breakdown of what that actually means here: [Trump's Psychedelic Executive Order: 5 Things It Actually Changes in 2026](https://www.thepsychedelicdigest.com/blog/trump-psychedelic-executive-order-2026).

The headline made the rounds. The field celebrated cautiously. The world moved on.

But we want to sit with a different question. A more philosophical one.

What if Trump did not just sign the order?

What if he actually tried it?

## What Is a Heroic Dose?

For the uninitiated: a heroic dose, a term popularised by ethnobotanist and philosopher Terence McKenna, refers to a very high dose of psilocybin mushrooms — typically five grams or more, taken in silent darkness, alone. No distractions. No screens. No advisors whispering in your ear.

McKenna believed that at this dose, the ego does not just soften. It dissolves entirely. What is left is something closer to raw perception. A sense of profound interconnection with other humans, with nature, with the consequences of your own actions.

He argued, with characteristic wit and genuine seriousness, that the planet's problems were largely problems of ego. Of leaders so enclosed in their own certainty that they had lost the capacity to feel the weight of their decisions on other human lives.

He was not entirely wrong.

## The Science Behind the Joke

Here is where the satire becomes genuinely interesting.

Psilocybin has been shown in multiple peer-reviewed studies to significantly reduce what researchers call "authoritarian thinking" — the tendency to defer to hierarchy, to value in-group loyalty over universal concern, and to perceive the world in rigid us-versus-them frameworks.

A 2017 study published in Psychopharmacology found that psilocybin reliably increases "nature relatedness" and decreases "authoritarianism" even months after a single dose. The effect was not subtle. It was one of the most robust psychological shifts the researchers had seen from a single intervention.

A 2023 meta-analysis in Neuroscience and Biobehavioral Reviews confirmed that psychedelics consistently increase empathy, perspective-taking, and what researchers call "openness to experience," one of the most stable predictors of reduced aggression and reduced support for military conflict.

In plain language: psychedelics tend to make people less interested in war.

Which brings us to the obvious question.

## The Military Already Knew This. That Is Why They Stopped.

In 1958, the US Army dosed soldiers at Edgewood Arsenal with LSD to explore its potential as a chemical weapon. The idea was to use it against enemy troops — to render them incapacitated, confused, unable to follow orders.

What they found was more interesting than incapacitation.

The soldiers became friendly. They laughed. They found it difficult to treat the exercise as a threat. One man reportedly could not stop expressing concern for the wellbeing of his fellow troops.

Across the Atlantic, the British Army ran their own version in 1964. Operation Moneybags, conducted at Porton Down, dosed seventeen Royal Marine Commandos with LSD and sent them into a field exercise. The film footage, now publicly available through the Imperial War Museum, shows what followed: men giggling uncontrollably, one attempting to cut down a tree with his spade, another climbing the same tree to talk to it. The commanding officer, struggling to maintain composure, radioed in that he urgently needed assistance because "things are getting rather out of hand."

The program was discontinued.

Not, the record suggests, because the drug failed to have an effect. But because the effect it had was entirely the wrong one for military purposes.

Empathy, it turns out, is a very poor foundation for a fighting force.

## Nixon Knew Too. He Just Had Different Plans.

Here is where the history stops being funny.

In 1994, John Ehrlichman, President Nixon's domestic policy advisor and Watergate co-conspirator, gave an interview to journalist Dan Baum that would not be published until Harper's Magazine ran it in 2016.

In it, Ehrlichman was unusually direct.

He told Baum that the Nixon administration had two enemies in 1968: the antiwar left and Black communities. And since they could not make it illegal to oppose the war or to be Black, they did the next best thing. They associated the antiwar left with marijuana and Black communities with heroin, then criminalised both as heavily as they could.

His closing line: "Did we know we were lying about the drugs? Of course we did."

Psychedelics were not banned because they were dangerous. They were banned because the people who took them tended to become very difficult to send to war.

## Trump's Order May Be His Own Worst Idea

Here is the irony that keeps us up at night.

Trump signed an executive order to accelerate psychedelic research, almost certainly with the backing of veteran advocacy groups and the bipartisan goodwill that comes from helping soldiers with PTSD.

These are genuine, worthy goals.

But the downstream effect of a more psychedelic-literate population is, historically, a less war-tolerant one. The research on this is not ambiguous. Populations with higher rates of psychedelic experience consistently show lower support for military intervention, lower authoritarian political preferences, and higher prioritisation of diplomacy and international cooperation.

If Trump's order works as intended, and millions of Americans access psychedelic therapy over the coming decade, the political appetite for conflicts like the one currently threatening to escalate with Iran will shrink considerably.

He may have accidentally accelerated the very movement that makes the next war harder to sell.

McKenna, were he still alive, would probably find this extremely funny.

## The Hopeful Part

We are not seriously suggesting that world leaders should be dosed without consent. That would be unethical, illegal, and almost certainly a diplomatic incident.

But we are seriously noting something that the science keeps returning to.

The fundamental precondition for large-scale violence is the psychological capacity to see other human beings as abstractions. As threats. As acceptable casualties in service of a larger strategy.

Psychedelics, across decades of research, appear to reliably erode that capacity.

They do not make people passive. They make people more capable of feeling the full weight of a decision's consequences across all the humans it will affect.

That is not a political position. That is a neurological one.

And in a week when the world is watching two nuclear-armed governments exchange rhetoric about Iran, it is worth sitting with the question that Terence McKenna never stopped asking:

What would our leaders decide, if they could actually feel what their decisions do to other people?

We do not know the answer.

But we suspect it would involve considerably fewer missiles.

